(465, 4, '2014-12-30 17:39:32', '2014-12-30 17:39:32', '[vc_row][vc_column][vc_column_text]Owners have raced greyhounds for many years and race goers see them muzzled, chasing a make believe hare. The public gain a lot of excitement from the spectacle and gamble thousands of pounds on their performance. When they have finished their usual track life, either because they are too old, injured, or just not fast enough, they are disposed of. The lucky ones end up in Greyhound Rescue for re-homing as family pets.\n\nThe problem they then have is overcoming the public''s image of the breed. It is generally thought that they need to be kept muzzled, are dangerous around children and need lots of exercise.\n\nAs with all breeds each greyhound has it''s own temperament but in general greyhounds are extremely lazy, spending most of their time either flat on their backs, with their legs in the air, or sprawled out in their bed fast asleep. Most only need two walks a day and the freedom of an enclosed back garden. They love a cuddle and in particular like their bellies rubbed.\n\nA greyhound sees a lot further than a human being and if they see something in the distance they will set off to chase it, so it is wise to keep them on a lead at all times when walking them, but they saunter along at a genteel pace, giving the owners a steady walk.\n\nIn general a Greyhound is one of the most loving pets to own and will give many years of love and friendship to it''s lucky owner.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row][vc_column width="1/1"][vc_cta_button call_text="If you are interested in learning more about greyhounds, please ask us anything and we''ll do our best to help. " title="Get In Touch" target="_self" color="btn-primary" icon="wpb_arrow" size="wpb_regularsize" position="cta_align_right"][/vc_column][/vc_row]', 'About Greyhounds', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '89-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-12-30 17:39:32', '2014-12-30 17:39:32', '', 89, 'http://www.greyhoundrescue.org.uk/89-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(415, 1, '2014-11-03 16:50:17', '2014-11-03 16:50:17', '&nbsp;\r\n\r\nI first met Gamble in 2005 when Karen introduced me to him and within hours he became the love of my life....as all greyhounds do. He was such a big strong sloppy clown. A very playful boy who I will adore until forever. I lost him on the 2nd November 2011 and it is a day although I wish I could block out of my mind, I know I never will. He died in my arms at 3.45am. He should not have gone at that time and was due to a dental.\r\n\r\nMe, Beau &amp; Karen miss you so much my boy but I know you are here with me even though I cannot feel you physically.\r\n\r\nI will never say goodbye, only goodnight young man. xxxx\r\n\r\nMummy', 'Gamble', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'gamble', '', '', '2014-11-10 16:26:05', '2014-11-10 16:26:05', '', 0, 'http://www.greyhoundrescue.org.uk/?p=415', 0, 'post', '', 0),
